QDES. BOOK 1. 273

ODE XX.

Quinctilius Varus, a distinguished poet of Cremona, was the intimate and mutual friend of Horace and Virgil, but perhaps endeared to no one more than to the latter. He died in the seven hundred and twenty-ninth year of Rome. The death of Varus was most deeply felt by Virgil, to whom this ode is ad- dressed by way of condolence.

2. Praecipe . . . Melpomene : ‘ O Melpomene, teach me mourn- ful strains.’ Horace, with much propriety, invokes the Muse of Tragedy to aid him in the tribute he is about to pay to the worth of their lamented friend3 for whom no measure of grief seemed to be excessive.

ll. Non ita . . . deos : i. e. you request the gods to restore you Quinctilius, who was not given you on the condition that he was not to be taken away.

ODE XXI.

Lucius AElius Lamia, a poet of considerable reputation, and a friend of Horace, had in the civil dissensions joined the repub- licans. After the downfall of his party, he became despondent, and thought the commonwealth was going to ruin.
